---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="SEOplant vs Byword — Which AI SEO Tool Is Right for You?"
  description="Head-to-head comparison: SEOplant vs Byword.ai. Features, pricing, programmatic SEO capabilities, and which tool fits your needs in 2026."
  canonicalUrl="https://seoplant.io/vs/byword"
  type="article"
>

  <article style="max-width:800px;margin:0 auto;padding:var(--space-2xl) var(--space-lg);">
    <p style="color:var(--color-text-muted);font-size:0.9rem;">Updated: May 2026 &middot; 8 min read</p>

    <h1>SEOplant vs Byword: Which AI SEO Tool Wins in 2026?</h1>

    <p class="lead">If you're building SEO content at scale, two tools stand out: <strong>SEOplant</strong> (open-source, full-site generation) and <strong>Byword</strong> (AI content writer with pSEO templates). Here's the honest comparison.</p>

    <div class="verdict-box">
      <h3>TL;DR</h3>
      <p><strong>Choose Byword</strong> if you already have a WordPress/Webflow site and just need AI-written articles.</p>
      <p><strong>Choose SEOplant</strong> if you want the entire site — SEO strategy, design, content, deployment — from a single keyword, with no vendor lock-in.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Quick Comparison</h2>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>SEOplant</th><th>Byword</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Starting Price</strong></td><td class="win">Free / $79/mo</td><td>$99/mo</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Programmatic SEO</strong></td><td class="win">Template + Dataset → full site</td><td>Template-based articles only</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Competitor Analysis</strong></td><td class="win">Auto crawl + SWOT + gap analysis</td><td class="lose">Not included</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>SEO Strategy Generation</strong></td><td class="win">Topic clusters + 6-month calendar</td><td class="lose">Not included</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Website Building</strong></td><td class="win">Astro static site, full export</td><td class="lose">No site building</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Content Generation</strong></td><td>Markdown/MDX, AI-assisted</td><td class="win">GPT-4, research-backed, fast</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>CMS Integrations</strong></td><td>Directus (self-hosted)</td><td class="win">6 platforms (WP, Webflow, Ghost, Shopify, HubSpot, Notion)</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>GEO Optimization</strong></td><td class="win">Built-in llms.txt + Schema + AI tracking</td><td class="lose">Not included</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Deployment</strong></td><td class="win">VPS / Vercel / Cloudflare, no lock-in</td><td class="lose">Content only, no deployment</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Open Source</strong></td><td class="win">MIT license</td><td class="lose">Proprietary</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Code Export</strong></td><td class="win">Full site export, you own it</td><td class="lose">No code to export</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2>When to Choose Byword</h2>
    <p>Byword is the better choice when:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>You already have a WordPress or Webflow site and need to scale content production</li>
      <li>You bring your own keyword research (Byword doesn't do keyword discovery)</li>
      <li>You need rapid article generation — Byword's GPT-4 pipeline is fast (under 2 minutes per article)</li>
      <li>You want multi-CMS publishing — Byword integrates with 6 platforms out of the box</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Bottom line:</strong> Byword is a content engine. It writes articles. You still need to build and maintain the site, do keyword research, plan content strategy, and handle deployment yourself.</p>

    <h2>When to Choose SEOplant</h2>
    <p>SEOplant wins when:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>You're starting from scratch — one keyword becomes a complete, deployed website</li>
      <li>You want automated competitor analysis and SEO strategy, not just content</li>
      <li>You hate vendor lock-in — export your full site code, deploy anywhere, no proprietary format</li>
      <li>You need programmatic SEO at the site level (URL structure, internal linking, schema, not just articles)</li>
      <li>You're technical or work with developers — the open-source CLI gives you full control</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Bottom line:</strong> SEOplant is an SEO website factory. It doesn't just write content — it builds the strategy, the site, the schema, the internal linking, and deploys everything. Content generation is one part of a much larger pipeline.</p>

    <h2>Cost Comparison: 1 Year of Building SEO Sites</h2>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>What You Need</th><th>SEOplant (Cloud)</th><th>Byword + Other Tools</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>AI content generation</td><td>Included (2,000 credits/mo)</td><td>$99/mo (Byword Starter)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Keyword research</td><td>Included (DataForSEO)</td><td>$129/mo (Ahrefs)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Website hosting</td><td>Included (Vercel/VPS)</td><td>$20/mo (WP hosting)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>SEO monitoring</td><td>Included (rank tracking)</td><td>$79/mo (Surfer add-on)</td></tr>
          <tr style="font-weight:700;"><td>Annual Total</td><td class="win">$948</td><td>$3,924</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2>The Verdict</h2>
    <p>If you're an existing site owner who just needs to scale article production, <strong>Byword</strong> is a great tool. Its content quality is solid and the CMS integrations are convenient.</p>
    <p>But if you're building SEO sites — whether for yourself or clients — and you want the entire pipeline automated (research → strategy → site → content → deploy → monitor), <strong>SEOplant</strong> is the only tool that does it all. And it costs less than a quarter of what you'd spend stitching together separate tools.</p>

    <div style="background:var(--color-surface);border:1px solid var(--color-border);border-radius:12px;padding:24px;text-align:center;margin-top:32px;">
      <h3 style="margin-bottom:8px;">Try SEOplant Free</h3>
      <p style="color:var(--color-text-muted);margin-bottom:16px;">Open source (MIT). Or use the cloud version with real SEO data.</p>
      <a href="https://app.seoplant.io/dashboard" class="btn btn-primary">Get Started</a>
      <a href="https://github.com/seoplant/seoplant" class="btn btn-secondary" style="margin-left:10px;">GitHub</a>
    </div>
  </article>

</BaseLayout>

